Internet police crack  
down on term paper
black market

Boston University has begun policing the
Internet for sites that illegally sell term papers. Last
month it charged several companies in federal court
with wire fraud, mail fraud, racketeering, and violat-
ing a Massachusetts law that bans the sale of term
papers. Through an undercover investigator posing
as a desperate college student, the university duped
these companies into selling term papers to her.

This story brings up several tricky issues.

First of all, any student who buys term papers
should be ashamed for being so stupid. Not just too
stupid to write a paper, but so stupid as to actually
pay as much as $175 to buy one while paying thou-
sands more to attend college. '

These poor fools could save a lot of time -and
money if they just bought counterfeit diplomas
instead. You don’t even need an Internet connection
for that — just a laser printer, nice parchment paper.
from Kinkos and Adobe Pagemaker, which would
cost far less than going to school and buying papers.
They could save a lot of money that way and still
obtain worthless pieces of paper that will help them
find jobs they’re not really qualified for and won’t
be able to keep.

Also, there should be laws in every state banning
the sale of term papers, and any school that respects
its alumni should have mandatory expulsion policy
for students who buy them. While most students put
in long hours in libraries and computing labs writing
papers the night before they’re due, it is an abuse of
freedom for others to just buy their grades. That
makes diplomas earned by hard work almost worth-
less too. Nobody can tell later who worked and
earned theirs and who didn’t.

Anybody caught buying term papers should be
immediately ejected and expelled from school.

Perhaps BU has extra time on its hands now
without a football program —— but it’s not Boston
University’s job to police the Internet. It is responsi-
ble for protecting the integrity of the academic insti-
tution, but that doesn’t mean playing undercover
secret agent and trying to entrap small online busi-
nesses.

