This letter is concerning the column
“You shouldn’t be teaching if you can’t
speak the language.” I must take exception
with Dan Ertinan’s views on teaching assis-
tants. Here are my thoughts regarding each
of his three main points:

(1) “There should be a ﬂuency test for
TAs” —-— Regarding ﬂuency, I agree that
TAs should be fairly proﬁcient in the
English language. However, I feel that Mr.
Ertman was far too harsh on this point. I
currently have an Asian TA in one class,
and although she occasionally “butchers”
certain grammatical riﬂes, her vocabulary is
so vastly superior to 75 percent of the cam-
pus, I can hardly fault her for sometimes
using the incorrect verb tense. Furthermore,
she is obviously trying very hard and I do
not see why the student body is so unwill-
ing to encourage people like her. Most

Americans never even come close to that
level of ﬂuency in another language. I give
these people a lot of credit just for the

attempt. English is, as everybody knows, —

the language with the most exceptions.

(2) “The TA should know the material per-
fectly” —— Perhaps Mr. Ertman always had
spectacular professors and teachers in his
educational career. However, I am sure that
most students would agree with me that
even ﬁill professors occasionally cannot
answer a question or solve a problem the
very first time they look at it. It is unrea-
sonable to expect a TA, who has not ﬁn-
ished his education yet, to be able to answer
any question about anything related to a
particular subject. And if someone is so
“easily persuaded” to stop attending recita-
tion sections, I don’t see why the fact that it
contributes to his grade isn’t enough incen-
tive on its own. We are here to learn, not be
entertained.

(3) “The TA should be on time and have
time for students” —— I agree that a TA
should always be on time for classes. But
Mr. Ertrnan seems to be brushing aside the
fact that students are almost always the cul-
prits when it comes to being late.

Maybe Mr. Ertman should put the
responsibility for learning where it belongs
—— on the student.

