The Orangemen went into the half with
a commanding 19-0 lead. Syracuse had 324
total yard to Pitt’s 77. It was a lopsided
matchup by anyone’s standards. But, there
was still a half-hour of football left.

On Pitt’s second possession of the sec-
ond half—hour, the Panthers faced a fourth-
and—one on their own 35. With a 19-point
deﬁcit in front of them and the noise of the
Pitt student section at their backs, Coach
Walt Harris decided to go for it.

“I wasn’t trying to be a hero, just want-
ed to give the ‘D’ some hope,” said Harris.

Gonzalez sneaked for the ﬁrst down,
but just three plays later, the Panthers were
forced to punt from the Pitt 43.

Punter Grant Cofﬁeld received the snap
and threw the ball downﬁeld to wide-open
linebacker Ernest Coakley for a 25-yard
gain and a ﬁrst down on the SU 38.

“All week it [the fake punt] was there.
It gave us a spark when we really needed it,”
said Hanis.

The team fed oil“ that spark and cashed
in when Gonzalez threw a ﬁve-yard touch-
down pass to Jake Hoifart. Gonzalez took
the two-point conversion in himself to cut
the score to 19-8.

But the thought of a comeback nearly
vanished when Sy1acuse’s Kevin Johnson
struck, returning Coﬁield’s ensuing kickoff
91 yards for a touchdown.

“The kick retum was momentous. We
have struggled in special teams,” Harris
said. “Grant did a good job all day, he just
didn’t kick it deep enough.”

Gonzalez responded with a 28-yard
touchdown pass to wideout Terry Murphy,
cutting the deﬁcit to 11.

This is where the Pitt “D” found its
“hope.” It held the varmted Syracuse offense
to three plays and out on an abortive Orange
drive, highlighted by an Eric Kasperowicz
sack of McNabb.

“We made some big plays. We wanted
to give the offense a chance,” said
Kasperowicz.

The offense took the chance it was
given, and when Billy West scored midway
through the fourth, the score went to 26-21.

After another defensive stop, Pitt found
itself at its own six with just over three min-
utes remaining. The Panthers needed 94
yards to take the lead.

Gonzalez began the drive with two runs
totaling 17 yards. Then he went deep to a
well-covered Terry Murphy, who made a
miraculous catch for a 41-yard gain. The
quarterback threw for a quick ﬁrst down
before hitting fullback Tony Thompson at
the SU 1-yand-line. West plowed in for a
another touchdown to give Pitt a 27-26 lead.

But, the drive went for naught.
McNabb would lead the Orange on an
eight-play, 65-yard drive of his own, ending
with a touchdown pass to Quinton
Spotwood that secured the win for Syracuse.

“There were a couple teams battling out
there today,” said Harris. “I give a tremen-
dous amount of credit to our defense who

played hard all day. I’m proud to be associ- ‘

ated with all of them.”

