Linguistics is the science of language. Course offerings for Spring 1997
include the following:

LING 0080 Aspects of language
Text: Steven Pinker’s bestseller, The Language Instinct. Fulfills Social Science
and Public Policy Issues GE requirements. No prerequisite.

Language is at the center of human existence. The activities that ﬁll our days -
politics and romance, business and education, entertainment and warfare -
require the uniquely human ability to use and understand language. We all have
questions about the nature of this ability. How is language mastered and used?
Can animals learn it? What about computers? Are some languages better than
others? How does the language we learn affect how we think? This course
addresses these questions.

LING I 930 Introduction to Applied Linguistics

Thinking of graduate school in language education or foreign languages, or of
teaching English overseas? Try learning about language teaching, language and
the law, language writing systems, and stylistics in Applied Linguistics.
Prerequisite: LING 0080, LING 1950, or study of a foreign language. Contact
iul’fs+@pitt.edu for further details.

LING I 950 Introduction to Linguistics

A survey of general linguistics, focussing on the structure of human language:
its sounds, word structures, and syntax. Gain an appreciation for the wonders of
human language, the variety and complexity of its structure, and the subtlety of
its use. No prerequisite.

LING I 951 Languages of the World

This course is organized around two central questions: (1) How do languages
differ from one another? (2) What are some social and political consequences
of language contact? Each student will select one language family to investigate
through a series of weekly assignments. No prerequisite. Contact

sally@isp.pitt.eidu for more information.

Questions? Contact the Department of Linguistics at 624-5916 or 624-5900.

